      ## Launching a usability test

      As a followup to the A/B test, I decided to run a usability test to try and <em>better understand why there was a significant drop in clickouts</em>. I also saw this is a learning opportunity to setup and launch my own test.

      I decided to use the “Navigation test” on UsabilityHub, because I wanted to simulate the following scenario:

      1. The user sees a list of prices for for their chosen hotel.
      2. The user “clicks out” on the Hotels.com price, opening the partner website within the browser view.
      3. The user wants to <em>navigate back to the list of prices</em>, so they can explore other offers.

      I would see what percentage of users would <em>successfully know how to navigate back</em> to the list of prices. Five variations were tested:

      1. Back icon, positioned on the <em>left</em> of the screen.
      2. Close icon, positioned on the <em>left</em> of the screen.
      3. “Close” text, positioned on the <em>left</em> of the screen.
      4. Close icon, positioned on the <em>right</em> of the screen.
      5. “Close” text, positioned on the <em>right</em> of the screen.

